description: An iconic symbol of Paris, the Eiffel Tower is a wrought-iron lattice tower on the Champ de Mars, named after the engineer Gustave Eiffel.
The Great Wall of China is a series of fortifications that were built across the historical northern borders of China to protect against various nomadic groups.
The Statue of Liberty is a colossal neoclassical sculpture on Liberty Island in New York Harbor, a gift from the people of France to the United States.
The Colosseum is an ancient amphitheater in the center of the city of Rome, Italy. It is the largest ancient amphitheater ever built and is still the largest standing amphitheater in the world today.
Machu Picchu is a 15th-century Inca citadel located in the Eastern Cordillera of southern Peru on a mountain ridge 2,430 meters above sea level.
Christ the Redeemer is an iconic statue of Jesus Christ in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, located at the peak of the 700-meter Corcovado mountain in the Tijuca Forest National Park.
The Taj Mahal is an ivory-white marble mausoleum on the south bank of the Yamuna river in the Indian city of Agra. It was commissioned in 1632 by the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan.
The Sydney Opera House is a multi-venue performing arts centre at Sydney Harbour in Sydney, Australia. It is one of the 20th century's most famous and distinctive buildings.
The Pyramids of Giza are ancient pyramid structures in the Giza pyramid complex on the outskirts of Cairo, Egypt. They are one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World.
The Golden Gate Bridge is a suspension bridge spanning the Golden Gate, the one-mile-wide strait connecting San Francisco Bay and the Pacific Ocean.
Petra is a historical and archaeological city in southern Jordan. Famous for its rock-cut architecture and water conduit system, Petra is also called the 'Rose City'.
Mount Everest is Earth's highest mountain above sea level, located in the Mahalangur Himal sub-range of the Himalayas. The Chinaâ€“Nepal border runs across its summit point.
Big Ben is the nickname for the Great Bell of the clock at the north end of the Palace of Westminster in London, and often extended to refer to the clock and the clock tower.

The Acropolis of Athens is an ancient citadel located on a rocky outcrop above the city of Athens and contains the remains of several ancient buildings of great architectural and historic significance.
Stonehenge is a prehistoric monument in Wiltshire, England. It consists of a ring of standing stones, each around 13 feet high, seven feet wide, and weighing approximately 25 tons.
The Grand Canyon is a steep-sided canyon carved by the Colorado River in Arizona, United States. It is considered one of the wonders of the natural world.
Santorini is one of the Cyclades islands in the Aegean Sea. It was devastated by a volcanic eruption in the 16th century BC, forever shaping its rugged landscape.
The Burj Khalifa is a skyscraper in Dubai, United Arab Emirates. With a total height of 829.8 m, it has been the tallest structure and building in the world since its topping out in 2009.
Mount Fuji, located on Honshu Island, is the highest mountain in Japan, standing 3,776.24 m. It is an active stratovolcano that last erupted in 1707â€“1708.
Neuschwanstein Castle is a 19th-century Romanesque Revival palace on a rugged hill above the village of Hohenschwangau near FÃ¼ssen in southwest Bavaria, Germany.
Angkor Wat is a temple complex in Cambodia and is the largest religious monument in the world, on a site measuring 162.6 hectares.
The BasÃ­lica de la Sagrada FamÃ­lia is a large unfinished Roman Catholic minor basilica in Barcelona, designed by Catalan architect Antoni GaudÃ­.
Chichen Itza was a large pre-Columbian city built by the Maya people of the Terminal Classic period. It is located in TinÃºm Municipality, YucatÃ¡n State, Mexico.
Niagara Falls is a group of three waterfalls at the southern end of Niagara Gorge, spanning the border between the province of Ontario in Canada and the state of New York in the United States.
The Louvre Museum is the world's largest art museum and a historic monument in Paris, France. It is best known for being the home of the Mona Lisa.

The GalÃ¡pagos Islands, part of Ecuador, are considered one of the world's foremost destinations for wildlife-viewing. Their isolated terrain shelters a diversity of plant and animal species, many found nowhere else.
The Palace of Versailles, is a former royal residence located in Versailles, about 12 miles west of Paris, France. It is renowned for its opulent architecture and expansive gardens.
Table Mountain is a flat-topped mountain forming a prominent landmark overlooking the city of Cape Town in South Africa.
Victoria Falls is a waterfall on the Zambezi River in southern Africa, which provides habitat for several unique species of plants and animals.
The Brandenburg Gate is an 18th-century neoclassical monument in Berlin, built on the orders of Prussian king Frederick William II.
Moai are monolithic human figures carved by the Rapa Nui people on Easter Island in eastern Polynesia between 1250 and 1500 CE.
The Badshahi Mosque is a Mughal era mosque in Lahore, Pakistan. Commissioned by Emperor Aurangzeb in 1671, it is the largest mosque of the Mughal-era and the second largest mosque in Pakistan.
The Shalimar Gardens are a Mughal garden complex located in Lahore, Pakistan. Construction of the gardens began in 1641 during the reign of Emperor Shah Jahan and was completed in 1642.

Minar-e-Pakistan is a national monument located in Lahore, Pakistan. It was built to commemorate the Lahore Resolution, which was passed on 23rd March 1940, and is considered the first official call for a separate homeland for the Muslims of the Indian subcontinent.

The Wazir Khan Mosque is a 17th-century mosque located in the city of Lahore, capital of the Pakistani province of Punjab. The mosque was commissioned during the reign of the Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan as part of an ensemble of buildings that also included the nearby Shahi Hammam baths.

The Lahore Museum, located in the city of Lahore, was established in 1865 during the British colonial period. It houses a large collection of Buddhist art, Mughal and Sikh artifacts, and ancient manuscripts.

Jahangir's Tomb is the mausoleum built for the Mughal Emperor Jahangir. Located in Shahdara Bagh in Lahore, it is a significant example of Mughal architecture and was built by his son, Emperor Shah Jahan.
Hazuri Bagh is a garden built by Maharaja Ranjit Singh in 1818. It is located between the Badshahi Mosque and the Lahore Fort, featuring a baradari, which was used as a venue for state functions.
Established in 1872, Lahore Zoo is one of the oldest zoos in the world. It is a major tourist attraction in Lahore, housing a diverse range of animal species.

Liberty Market is a popular shopping area in Lahore, known for its wide variety of shops, ranging from traditional handicrafts to modern fashion. It is a bustling area filled with locals and tourists alike.

The Faisal Mosque in Islamabad is the largest mosque in Pakistan. It was completed in 1986 and is named after the late King Faisal of Saudi Arabia. The mosque's unique design features eight-sided shell-shaped sloping roofs forming a triangular worship hall.
The Pakistan Monument is a national monument and heritage museum located in Islamabad. The blooming flower shape of the monument represents the four provinces and three territories of Pakistan.
Daman-e-Koh is a viewpoint and hilltop garden north of Islamabad. It offers panoramic views of the city and is a popular destination for tourists and locals.
Rawal Lake is an artificial reservoir that provides the water needs for the cities of Rawalpindi and Islamabad. The lake and its surroundings are a popular picnic spot.
The Lok Virsa Museum in Islamabad is a museum of traditional culture and folk heritage. It showcases the cultural heritage of Pakistan and various ethnic groups living in the country.
Mazar-e-Quaid, also known as the Jinnah Mausoleum, is the final resting place of Muhammad Ali Jinnah, the founder of Pakistan. It is an iconic symbol of Karachi and a popular tourist destination.

Clifton Beach, located in Karachi, is a popular destination for both locals and tourists. It offers a variety of recreational activities, including camel and horse riding, amusement parks, and restaurants.
Mohatta Palace is a museum located in Karachi. It was built by Shivratan Chandraratan Mohatta, a Hindu Marwari businessman, in 1927. The palace is an excellent example of Indo-Saracenic architecture.
Karachi Zoo, also known as Karachi Zoological Gardens, is one of the oldest zoos in Pakistan. It is home to a variety of animals and also features a natural history museum and a reptile house.
Frere Hall is a well-preserved building from the British colonial era, located in Karachi. It serves as a library and exhibition space and is surrounded by beautiful gardens.

Mohenjo-Daro is an ancient Indus Valley Civilization city that was built around 2500 BCE. Located in the Sindh province, it is one of the world's earliest major urban settlements and a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
Skardu is a town in the Gilgit-Baltistan region of Pakistan. It is known for its stunning landscapes, including high-altitude lakes, mountains, and the Deosai National Park.
Fairy Meadows is a grassland near Nanga Parbat in Gilgit-Baltistan, Pakistan. It offers stunning views of Nanga Parbat, the world's ninth-highest mountain, and is a popular camping site.

Swat Valley, located in the Khyber Pakhtunkhwa province of Pakistan, is often referred to as the 'Switzerland of the East.' It is known for its lush green valleys, rivers, and cultural heritage sites.

Hunza Valley is located in the Gilgit-Baltistan region of Pakistan. Known for its breathtaking landscapes, snow-capped mountains, and serene environment, it is a popular destination for tourists and trekkers.
